        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the words rendered ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "damnation, discerning, judged",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "condemnation",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", are all, in the original, parts or derivations of one and the same word; and so Wyclif admirably rendered them into the language of his day by words connected with one and the same English verb; “He that etith and drinkith vnworthili, etith and drinkith ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "doom",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " to him, not wisely ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "demyng",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
