  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 40.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - There is a change in the construction here, which is not marked in the Authorized Version. The sentence in this fortieth verse should stand alone, and be read thus: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "They which devour",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "οἱ κατεσθίοντες",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "widows' houses, and for a pretense make long prayers; these shall receive greater condemnation",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "cmt_word",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "widows' houses, and for a pretense make long prayers; these shall receive greater condemnation",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The sentence thus read is far more graphic. The statement thus becomes indeed more general, but the reference is still to the scribes who through their avarice swallowed up the property of helpless widows, and through their hypocrisy, in the hope of thus more effectually imposing upon their victims, lengthened out their prayers. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Greater condemnation.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The word in the Greek is ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "κρίμα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", that is, \"judgment.\" A severer sentence would fall upon them in the day of judgment and a heavier condemnation, because, under the semblance of piety, they practiced iniquity, and indulged their avarice under the mask of religion. Mark 12:40",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Vincent's Word Studies",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Widows' houses",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "People often left their whole fortune to the temple, and a good deal of the temple-money went, in the end, to the Scribes and Pharisees. The Scribes were universally employed in making wills and conveyances of property. They may have abused their influence with widows. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]